            <h2>What Is a Web Server?</h2>

            <p>
                Before we can talk about static web servers specifically, it helps to understand what 
                a web server is in general. A web server is basically a pool of information that your 
                computer accesses, kind of like a library. When your browser sends a request to a 
                website, the web server receives that request, and if it accepts it, it sends back 
                the HTML files, data, and other content your browser needs to display the page.
            </p>

            <!-- image of a client server diagram -->
            <div class="image-placeholder">
                (insert image) A simple diagram showing a laptop labeled "Client" sending 
                an arrow labeled "Request" to a tower server labeled "Web Server", and the server 
                sending an arrow labeled "Response / HTML" back to the laptop.
            </div>

            <p>
                There are two main types of web servers: static and dynamic. This page focuses on 
                static web servers. The next page covers dynamic servers.
            </p>

        </div>

        <!-- main content about static servers -->
        <div class="content-box">

            <h2>Static Web Servers Explained</h2>

            <p>
                A static web server is one that sends the exact same files and content to every 
                single person who visits, every single time. Nothing changes. Whatever is stored 
                on the server is exactly what you get. There is no customization, no user accounts, 
                and no changing data.
            </p>

            <p>
                Because of this simplicity, static sites are much faster than dynamic ones. The server 
                does not need to do any processing or database lookups before responding. It just 
                hands over the files and that is it.
            </p>

            <div class="highlight-box">
                <p>
                    Think of a static web server like a printed book. Every person who picks it up 
                    reads the exact same words. It never updates itself, but it is always available 
                    and always consistent.
                </p>
            </div>

        </div>

        <!-- reasons to use static servers -->
        <div class="content-box">

            <h2>When to Use a Static Web Server</h2>

            <p>There are several situations where a static server makes the most sense:</p>

            <ul>
                <li>When the content on the site does not need to change often</li>
                <li>When speed and performance are the top priority</li>
                <li>When you want a simpler, lower-cost hosting solution</li>
                <li>When security is especially important because there are fewer attack surfaces</li>
                <li>When you do not need user logins or personalized content</li>
            </ul>

        </div>

        <!-- real world examples section -->
        <div class="content-box">

            <h2>Real World Examples</h2>

            <p>
                A lot of businesses and organizations actually use static web servers even today. 
                Here are some common examples:
            </p>

            <!-- image of a restaurant menu website -->
            <div class="image-placeholder">
                (insert image) A screenshot style mockup of a simple restaurant website 
                showing a menu page with food items listed, representing a static business site.
            </div>

            <h3>Restaurants</h3>
            <p>
                Restaurants often use static sites to display their menus. A menu does not change 
                that often, and when someone is looking up a restaurant online they mostly just want 
                the address, hours, and what food is available. A static site handles all of that 
                perfectly without any extra overhead.
            </p>

            <h3>Contact and Informational Pages</h3>
            <p>
                Many small businesses use static sites as a kind of digital business card. 
                They put their phone number, address, hours, and maybe some photos. Contact 
                information rarely changes, so a static site is fast, cheap, and reliable for 
                this purpose.
            </p>

            <h3>Government Organizations</h3>
            <p>
                Certain government websites use static pages for informational content because 
                they want to minimize security risks. Since static servers do not have databases 
                connected to them, there is less for an attacker to target. This matters because 
                government sites can be high-value targets for hackers.
            </p>

        </div>

        <!-- security section -->
        <div class="content-box">

            <h2>Security Advantages of Static Servers</h2>

            <p>
                One of the biggest advantages of static web servers is security. Because there is 
                no database involved, certain common attacks simply cannot work against them. 
                One of the most common types of website attacks is called a SQL Injection attack.
            </p>

            <h3>What Is a SQL Injection Attack?</h3>

            <p>
                SQL stands for Structured Query Language, which is the language used to talk to 
                databases. An SQL injection attack is when a hacker inserts malicious code into 
                an input field on a website to try to manipulate or read the database behind it. 
                There are a couple of types:
            </p>

            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type of SQLi Attack</th>
                    <th>How It Works</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Error-Based SQLi</td>
                    <td>The attacker triggers error messages from the database to learn about its structure. It is basically trial and error.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Union-Based SQLi</td>
                    <td>The attacker uses the SQL UNION operator to combine results from the real query with their own injected query, pulling out extra data.</td>
                </tr>
            </table>

            <p>
                Since static web servers have no database attached, SQL injection attacks have 
                nothing to target. This makes them inherently more secure for certain use cases.
            </p>

        </div>

        <!-- summary section -->
        <div class="content-box">

            <h2>Summary</h2>

            <p>
                Static web servers are simple, fast, secure, and affordable. They are a great 
                choice for any project where the content is mostly fixed and does not need to 
                change based on who is viewing it. They are not the right tool for everything, 
                but for display only sites, informational pages, and small organizations, 
                they are often the best option available.
            </p>

            <p>
                In the next section, we will look at dynamic web servers and see how they handle 
                the situations where static servers fall short.
            </p>

